# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: attu-island
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] The **180th meridian** or **antimeridian** is the meridian 180° both east and west of the prime meridian in a geographical coordinate system.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] The longitude at this line can be given as either east or west.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] On Earth, the prime and 180th meridians form a great ellipse that divides the planet into the Western and Eastern Hemispheres.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] The antimeridian passes mostly through the open waters of the Pacific Ocean but also runs across land in Russia, Fiji, and Antarctica.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] An important function of this meridian is its use as the basis for the International Date Line, which snakes around national borders to maintain date consistency within the territories of Russia, the United States, Kiribati, Fiji and New Zealand.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] The only places where roads cross this meridian are in Fiji and Russia.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] Fiji has several such roads and some buildings very close to it.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] Russia has three roads in the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] Many geographic software libraries or data formats project the world to a rectangle; very often this rectangle is split exactly at the 180th meridian.
[src:attu-island/180th-meridian] This often makes it non-trivial to do simple tasks (like representing an area, or a line) over the 180th meridian.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:attu-island/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:attu-island/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] The **1930 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau one month from April 1, 1930, determined the resident population of the United States to be 122,775,046, an increase of 13.7 percent over the 106,021,537 persons enumerated during the 1920 census.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] It was the first time the effects of suburban sprawl were recorded when, during the Roaring Twenties, a significant portion of the working population of New York City moved to New Jersey, aided by the George Washington Bridge which permitted quick transport from the state to Manhattan.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] It was also the first in which a city in the Western United States (Los Angeles) reached a population of at least a million people.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1930 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in 1949, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is located on 2,667 rolls of microfilm, and available from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1930 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:attu-island/1930-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1930.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] The **1940 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 132,164,569, an increase of 7.6 percent over the 1930 population of 122,775,046 people.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] The census date of record was April 1, 1940.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] A number of new questions were asked including where people were five years before, highest educational grade achieved, and information about wages.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] This census introduced sampling techniques; one in 20 people were asked additional questions on the census form.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] Other innovations included a field test of the census in 1939.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] In addition, a sample of individuals were asked additional questions covering age at first marriage, fertility, and other topics.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 1940 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] Following completion of the census, the original enumeration sheets were microfilmed; after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] Code, access to personally identifiable information from census records was restricted for 72 years.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] Non-personally identifiable information Microdata from the 1940 census is freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] Also, aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] On April 2, 2012—72 years after the census was taken—microfilmed images of the 1940 census enumeration sheets were released to the public by the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] The records are indexed only by enumeration district upon initial release; several organizations are compiling indices, in some cases through crowdsourcing.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1940.
[src:attu-island/1940-united-states-census] During World War II, the Census Bureau responded to numerous information requests from US government agencies, including the US Army and the US Secret Service, to facilitate the internment of Japanese Americans.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] The **1980 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 226,545,805, an increase of 11.4% over the 203,184,772 persons enumerated during the 1970 census.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] It was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of 20 million people, as well as the first in which all states recorded populations of over 400,000.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] This was the first census to count Hispanic and Latino Americans as an ethnicity.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 1980 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 1980 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1980 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2052.
[src:attu-island/1980-united-states-census] Between the 1980 census and the 1990 census, the United States population increased by approximately 22,164,837 or 9.8%.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The **2000 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States on April 1, 2000, to be 281,421,906, an increase of 13.2 percent over the 248,709,873 people enumerated during the 1990 census.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] This was the twenty-second federal census and was at the time the largest civilly administered peacetime effort in the United States.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 2000 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] It would be the last census to include the "long form", since subsequent censuses, starting with the 2010 census, would be "short form" only, with the more detailed questions being replaced by the new American Community Survey.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 2000 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of over 30 million, as well as the first in which two states—California and Texas—recorded populations of more than 20 million.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Microdata from the 2000 census is freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2072.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The U.S. resident population includes the total number of people in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau also enumerated the residents of the U.S. territory of Puerto Rico; its population was 3,808,610, an 8.1% increase over the number from a decade earlier.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Regionally, the South and West experienced the bulk of the nation's population increase: 14,790,890 and 10,411,850, respectively.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] This meant that the mean center of U.S. population moved to Phelps County, Missouri.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The Northeastern United States grew by 2,785,149; the Midwest by 4,724,144.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The results of the census are used to determine how many congressional districts each state is apportioned.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Congress defines the formula, in accordance with Title 2 of the U.S.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Code, to reapportion among the states the 435 seats in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The apportionment population consists of the resident population of the fifty states, plus the overseas military and federal civilian employees and their dependents living with them who could be allocated to a state.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Each member of the House represents a population of about 647,000.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The populations of the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico are excluded from the apportionment population because they do not have voting seats in the U.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Since the first census in 1790, the decennial count has been the basis for the United States representative form of government.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Article I, Section II specifies that "The Number of Representatives shall not exceed one for every thirty Thousand, but each State shall have at Least one Representative." In 1790, each member of the House represented about 34,000 residents.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Since then, the House more than quadrupled in size, and in 1911 the number of representatives was fixed at 435.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Today, each member represents about 20 times as many constituents.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] In the years leading up to the 2000 census, there was substantial controversy over whether the Bureau should adjust census figures based on a follow-up survey, called the post-enumeration survey, of a sample of blocks.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] This recommendation was followed by the Secretary of Commerce (the official in charge of making the determination).
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] After the census was tabulated, Utah challenged the results in two different ways.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Utah was extremely close to gaining a fourth congressional seat, falling 857 people short, which in turn was allocated to North Carolina.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The margin was later shortened to 80 people, after the federal government discovered that it overcounted the population of North Carolina by 2,673 residents.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau counted members of the military and other federal civilian employees serving abroad as residents of their home state but did not count other people living outside the United States.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Utah claimed that people traveling abroad as religious missionaries should be counted as residents and that the failure to do so imposed a burden on Mormon religious practice.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Almost half of all Mormon missionaries, more than 11,000 people, were from Utah; only 102 came from North Carolina.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] If this policy were changed, then Utah would have received an additional seat instead of North Carolina.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] On November 26, 2002, the Supreme Court affirmed the lower court ruling that rejected Utah's efforts to have Mormon missionaries counted.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The state of Utah then filed another lawsuit alleging that the statistical methods used in computing the state populations were improper and cost Utah the seat.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau uses a method called imputation to assign a number of residents to addresses where residents cannot be reached after multiple efforts.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] While nationwide the imputation method added 0.4% to the population, the rate in Utah was 0.2%.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The state challenged that the use of imputation violates the Census Act of 1957 and that it also fails the Constitution's requirement in Article I, Section 2 that an "actual enumeration" be used for apportionment.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Evans*, made it to the Supreme Court, but Utah was again defeated.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The census forms did not include any questions regarding sexual orientation, making it impossible to compile data comparing heterosexual and homosexual populations.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] However, two questions *were* asked that allowed same-sex partnerships to be counted.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The questionnaires asked the sex of each person in a household and they asked what the relationship was between each of the members of the household.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Respondents could check "Husband/wife" or "unmarried partner" or a number of other relationships.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Responses were tabulated and the Census Bureau reported that there were more than 658,000 same-sex couples heading households in the United States.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] However, only about 25% of gay men and 40% of lesbians are in shared-household partnerships at any one time, according to non-census surveys.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] For every same-sex couple tallied in the census, there could be three to six more homosexual un-partnered individuals who would not be counted as gay.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The census reported that same-sex male couples numbered 336,001 and female same-sex couples numbered 329,522.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Extrapolating from those figures and the surveyed partnering habits of homosexuals, as many as 4.3 million homosexual adults could have been living in the U.S. in 2000.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The exact number cannot be known because the census did not count them specifically.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Bisexual and transgender populations were not counted, either, because there were no questions regarding this information.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Also unavailable is the number of additional same-sex couples living under the same roof as the first, though this applies to additional heterosexual couples as well.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The lack of accurate numbers makes it difficult for lawmakers who are considering legislation on hate crimes or social services for gay families with children.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] It also makes for less accuracy when predicting the fertility of a population.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Another issue that concerned gay rights advocates involved the automatic changing of data during the tabulation process.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] This automatic software data compiling method, called *allocation*, was designed to counteract mistakes and discrepancies in returned questionnaires.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] Forms that were filled out by two same-sex persons who checked the "Husband/wife" relationship box were treated as a discrepancy.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau explained that same-sex "Husband/wife" data samples were changed to "unmarried partner" by computer processing methods in 99% of the cases.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] In the remaining 1%, computer systems used one of two possibilities: a) one of the two listed sexes was changed, making the partnership appear heterosexual, or b) if the two partners were more than 15 years apart in age, they might have been reassigned into a familial parent/child relationship.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] The process of automatic reassignment of same-sex marriage data was initiated so that the Census Bureau would not contravene the Defense of Marriage Act passed in 1996.
[src:attu-island/2000-united-states-census] With allocation moving married same-sex couples to the unmarried partner category, social scientists lost information that could have been extracted relating to the social stability of a same-gender couple who identify themselves as married.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In the chain of the Aleutians, the islands immediately to the west of Attu are the Russian Commander Islands, 208 miles (181 nmi; 335 km) away (and on the other side of the International Date Line).
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Attu is about 20 by 35 miles (32 by 56 km) in size with a land area of 344.7 square miles (893 km2), making it the 23rd largest island in the United States.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Attu Station, a former Coast Guard LORAN station, is located at 52°51′N 173°11′E﻿ / ﻿52.850°N 173.183°E﻿ / 52.850; 173.183, making it one of the westernmost points of the United States relative to the rest of the country.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The population in the 2010 census was 20 people, all at the Attu Station, though all inhabitants left the island later that year when the station closed.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] It then became the largest uninhabited island in the United States.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The Battle of Attu was the only World War II land battle fought in territory that is now part of a U.S. state.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In 1982, the only significant trees on the island were those planted by American soldiers at a chapel constructed after the 1943 battle when the Japanese occupation was over; they have since gone.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The name *Attu* is the Unangan language (Aleut) name for the island.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Research of the large number of archaeological sites on the island suggests an estimated precontact population ranging from 2,000 to 5,000 Unangan (Aleut).
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Attu, being the nearest of the Aleutian Islands to Kamchatka, was the first of the islands exploited by Russian traders.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Russian explorer Aleksei Chirikov called the island Saint Theodore in 1742.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Russians stayed on the island several years at a stretch to hunt sea otters.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The Russians often clashed with the local Unangan people.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] After the initial wave of traders, European ships largely overlooked Attu.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The Aleuts were the primary inhabitants of the island prior to World War II.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] American authorities had previously evacuated about 880 Aleuts from villages elsewhere in the Aleutian Islands to the Alaska Panhandle, where about 75 of them died of various infectious diseases over two years.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Attu Village had not yet been evacuated when the Japanese invaded.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] At the time, the population consisted of 45 native Aleuts and two white Americans, Charles Foster Jones (1879–1942), a radio technician, originally from St.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Paris, Ohio, and his wife Etta (1879–1965), a schoolteacher, originally from Vineland, New Jersey.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The village consisted of several houses around Chichagof Harbor.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The 41 Attu inhabitants who survived the Japanese invasion were taken to a prison camp near Otaru, Hokkaidō.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Twenty-two of them died while they were imprisoned.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Jones, 63, was killed by the Japanese forces almost immediately after the invasion.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Jones, 63, was subsequently taken to the Bund Hotel in Yokohama, Japan, which also housed Australian prisoners of war from the 1942 Battle of Rabaul in Papua New Guinea.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Jones and the Australian prisoners were held at the Yokohama Yacht Club from 1942 to 1944, and then at the Totsuka prisoner of war camp until their release in August 1945.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Jones died in December 1965 at age 86 in Bradenton, Florida.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Before the Attu villagers were returned to the U.S., the American government stated publicly that it was not aware of their status.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In late September 1942, the Japanese garrison on Attu was transferred to Kiska, essentially leaving Attu unoccupied, but American forces made no attempt to reoccupy it at the time.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] On October 29, 1942, the Japanese reestablished a base on Attu at Holtz Bay under the command of Lt.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Initially, the garrison was about 500 troops, but through reinforcements, that number reached about 2,300 by March 10, 1943.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] No more reinforcements arrived after that time, owing mainly to the efforts of the U.S. naval force under Rear Admiral Charles "Soc" McMorris, and United States Navy submarines.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] McMorris had been assigned to interdict the Japanese supply and reinforcement convoys.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] After the sizable naval Battle of the Komandorski Islands, the Japanese abandoned their attempts to resupply its Aleutian garrisons by surface ships.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] From then on, only submarines were used for the resupply runs.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] On May 11, 1943, the American operation to recapture Attu began.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] A shortage of landing craft, unsuitable beaches, and equipment that failed to operate in the harsh weather caused great difficulties in projecting any force against the Japanese.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Many soldiers suffered from frostbite because essential supplies could not be landed, or having been landed, could not be moved to where they were needed.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Army vehicles would not work on the tundra.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The Japanese defenders under Colonel Yasuyo Yamasaki did not contest the landings, but dug in on high ground away from the shore.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] This led to bloody fighting: there were 3,929 U.S. casualties: 549 were killed, 1,148 were injured, 1,200 had severe cold injuries, 614 succumbed to infectious diseases, and 318 died of miscellaneous causes – largely from Japanese booby traps and from friendly fire.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The Japanese were defeated in Massacre Valley.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The death count for the Japanese was 2,035.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The Americans then built "Navy Town" near Massacre Bay.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] On May 29, the last of the Japanese forces suddenly attacked near Massacre Bay in one of the largest banzai charges of the Pacific campaign.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The charge, led by Colonel Yamasaki, penetrated U.S. lines far enough to encounter shocked rear-echelon units of the American force.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] After furious, brutal, close-quarter, and often hand-to-hand combat, the Japanese force was killed almost to the last man: only 28 prisoners were taken, none of them officers.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] U.S. burial teams counted 2,351 Japanese dead, but it was presumed that hundreds more had been buried by naval, air, and artillery bombardments over the course of the battle.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The Japanese Navy, realizing that their position was now untenable, evacuated Kiska three months later.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The United States Army Air Forces (USAAF) built a larger airfield, the Alexai Point Army Airfield, and then used it on July 10, 1943, as the base for an air attack on the Japanese-held Kurile Islands, now part of Russia.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] This was the first air attack on the Japanese "homelands" since the famous Doolittle Raid in 1942.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] On April 11, 1945, in a period of only two hours, at least nine Japanese incendiary balloons sent to start forest fires in the United States West Coast were intercepted and shot down near Attu by USAAF P-38 Lightning aircraft.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] After the war, the survivors of the Otaru prison camp were shipped to other Aleutian islands or to the mainland of Alaska.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The US government did not allow them to return, despite their intense desire to do so.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The United States government decided to construct a LORAN station on the southern tip of Attu, at Theodore Point.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] This installation was staffed by about twenty members of the United States Coast Guard.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The equipment to build the station came out of Holtz Bay and was ferried on barges and landing craft to Baxter Cove, about one mile east of the station.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Bulldozers were used to cut a road from Baxter Cove to Theodore Point.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In 1954, the station was moved to Casco Cove, near the former Navy Base at Massacre Bay.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] At the time, the airport on Attu was the westernmost airfield located in the U.S. to have scheduled passenger airline service.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In 1984, the "392" exchange in the 907 area code, which includes Attu (and whose rate center is on nearby Shemya Island), became the last telephone exchange in the United States to be upgraded to dial service.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Prior to that, all telephone calls to and from that exchange could only be placed with the assistance of an operator.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The battlefield area and subsequent military sites were declared a National Historic Landmark in 1985.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The battlefield is now part of Aleutian Islands World War II National Monument.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Department of the Interior, the government of Japan placed a monument on Engineer Hill, site of the hand-to-hand finale of the battle against the Japanese.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In July 2007, the boots and foot bones of a Japanese soldier were found on the island, and on May 23, 2008, the remains of two more Japanese soldiers were discovered by U.S.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Coast Guard Petty Officer 3rd Class Richard Brahm, a public affairs specialist who was a documentarian for the remains recovery team.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] More remains were located at the burial site, but were left untouched with plans to return at a later time and have them exhumed properly.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] On August 1, 2010, the United States Coast Guard LORAN station on Attu permanently ceased operation.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] On August 27, 2010, the station was decommissioned and the Coast Guard personnel left, leaving the island with no resident population.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] On June 7, 2012, the 70th anniversary of the Japanese invasion, Senator Lisa Murkowski and United States Coast Guard Rear Admiral Thomas Ostebo travelled to Attu and dedicated a memorial to Attu Village, its residents who died in Japanese captivity, and the survivors who were unable to return.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In 2015, Attu Island was visited by pilot and world circumnavigator Michael Smith.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The island was a crucial refueling stop for Smith as he made his way from Adak island in the Aleutian Islands to Japan.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] As the island is uninhabited, he had to first fly containers of fuel there and then return as part of the journey from Adak to Japan.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] He was advised against staying overnight as there are large rats on the island.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] After three months of efforts in digging up and removing contaminated soil from the island in the summer of 2016 via funding from the Formerly Used Defense Sites program, it was expected that further efforts would be required to finish the environmental clean up of the island.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In 2017, a 7.8 magnitude earthquake had its epicenter west of Attu.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In 2022, the island was visited by Mack Rutherford who made an emergency landing during a flight from Japan to Alaska.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] After staying overnight he was able to safely continue his journey the next day.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Census as the unincorporated Aleut village of "Attoo", which at the time consisted of the village on western Chichagof Harbor.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] It had 107 residents, consisting of 74 Aleuts, 32 "Creoles" (mixed Russian and Native) and 1 White resident.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] It did not return again on the census until 1930.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] It appeared on the 1940 census, two years before the Japanese invasion of the village and island.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] It did not return again until 1980, when it consisted of the naval station residents at Massacre Bay, and was made a census-designated place (CDP).
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The name was changed to Attu Naval Station and redesignated a CDP in 2000.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] It last appeared on the 2010 census, just before the closure of the station in August that year and the departure of its remaining residents.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] According to the Köppen climate classification system, Attu has a subpolar oceanic climate (*Cfc*; *Dfc* if the 0 °C isotherm is used) closely bordering on a tundra climate (*ET*).
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The weather on Attu is typically cloudy, rainy, and foggy.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Five or six days a week are likely to be rainy, and there are only about eight to ten clear days a year.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The rest of the time, even if rain is not falling, fog of varying density is the rule rather than the exception.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] There are 39–49 inches (990–1,240 mm) of annual rainfall and other precipitation, with the heaviest rains in the autumn and early winter.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Due to the strong oceanic influence, Attu's climate is exceptionally mild for its latitude, with summers much cooler and winters much warmer than more continental locations.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Attu was an important location in the world of competitive birding, whose goal is to see or hear the largest possible number of bird species within a specific geographic area during a specific time period.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Because it is so physically remote from other parts of North America, there are a number of bird species likely to be found on Attu that are not seen anywhere else on the continent.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] John Fitchen called the island "the Holy Grail of North American birding".
[src:attu-island/attu-island] During his record-setting big year of 1998, in which he identified a record 745 species (later revised to 748), Sandy Komito spent 29 days (May 10 – June 7) on the island.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Since the closure of Attu Station by the U.S.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Coast Guard in 2010, access by birders has been greatly restricted.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Birding tours can still reach Attu, but only by a multi-day boat trip from Adak Island.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] In a 2010 interview on the subject, Al Levantin (one of Komito's competitors in the 1998 season) singled out inaccessibility of Attu as the factor that would make it nearly impossible to break Komito's record.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] However, Neil Hayward did break the record, by one species, in 2013 without visiting Attu.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Prior to World War II, the Bureau of Indian Affairs (BIA) operated the sole school on the island.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] When the Japanese captured Attu, the school had a single teacher who was a White American woman.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] A force consisting of 1,140 infantry under Major Matsutoshi Hosumi took control of the island and captured Attu's population, which consisted of 45 Aleuts and two white Americans, Charles Foster Jones (1879–1942), an amateur radio operator and weather reporter, originally from St.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Paris, Ohio, and his wife Etta (1879–1965), a teacher and nurse, originally from Vineland, New Jersey.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Charles Jones was killed by the Japanese forces immediately after the invasion because he refused to fix the radio he destroyed to prevent the occupying troops from using it.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] His wife was subsequently taken to the Bund Hotel in Yokohama, Japan, and later transferred to the Yokohama Yacht Club and kept there until July 1944 when she was moved to the old Totsuka Hospital in Yokohama.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] The hospital served as an internment camp until the end of the war in August 1945.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] Etta Jones died in December 1965 at age 86 in Bradenton, Florida.
[src:attu-island/attu-island] As of 2017, the uninhabited island is physically within the Aleutian Region School District.
